         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... from the prison of the (Sa)ṃsāra ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #a7 #a8 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6 #b7 #b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1949"/><citedRange>II, 79</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I will ... , you must not go, killing (us?) ....</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (Not) for this must be watched [out], (from the house I go) ....</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the (orna)ments (of monkhood) I wish to acquire ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... things. All ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... headhair ... This one ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... desired (?) ....</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the being would make ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... of every root of healing ....</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... sixteen myriads ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having spoken individually ....</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (therefo)re by him [there is] pure ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... for this reason must be endured ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (must) always pass ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (must) certainly (be done?) ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">There is a great likelihood that this fragment and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht67"/> belong to one and the same leaf. The 4x11-syllable-metre (rhythm = 6/5) we have already met in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht64"/>. Since only one strophe number (8) is preserved in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht67"/>, and because of the scantiness of the fragments, recto and verso side cannot be determined with any certainty. The translation, too, is frequently in the dark. Between the fragments there appears to be a gap of about 10-12 syllables.</note><note type="remarks">The original manuscript is missing, but was a narrow strip to the right of the schnurloch, composed of two fragments, badly damaged.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendation according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>93 f</citedRange></bibl>n. 9 based on <bibl><title corresp="ref:tht0000"/></bibl> 67 a2.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks"><hi>/// m(a)r</hi> is certainly a 1.sg. middle ending. Whether one can restore <hi>(yām)m(a)r</hi> "I will make" (as per Sieg/Siegling), remains uncertian.</note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">Since <hi>matsi – piyoṃ</hi> makes a colon of six syllables, <hi>matsi</hi> has to be a complete form, i.e. it is the nom. or obl. noun 'headhair'. This makes it very unlikely that <hi>piyoṃ</hi> is a variant of the 3pl. Imp of <hi>pi<hi rend="superscript">ā</hi>-</hi> ‘± to make a sound like a trumpet’ (see most recently <bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2010"/><citedRange>723</citedRange></bibl>). Therefore Malzahn now suggest to separate <hi>p iyoṃ</hi>, <hi>iyoṃ</hi> being the 3.pl. Imp of <hi>iyā-</hi> ‘to cause to go', while the lacuna may be restored to <hi>(ṣa)p</hi>. Since the text is praising the superiority of moonkhood, one may think of a sense like "they caused them to go shave their hair".</note><note corresp="#b8" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>94 f</citedRange></bibl>n. 3 <hi>nemñceksa</hi> stands for <hi>nemñcek tsa</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b8" type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">Sieg/Siegling propose to restore to <hi>yā(mṣle)</hi> "must be done".</note></p>
         </div>
